				\begin{document}$$\tau_{\text{m}} = \, C_{\text{m}} R \, ( 1/{{\lambda }}_{\text{int}} + 1/ 2 {{\lambda }}_{\text{ext}} )$$\end{document}The charging (τm) time for Escherichia coli was found to be 17–50 μs in a 3 μS/cm (low conductivity) buffer ([25]. In the 0.2 mS/cm and 1 mS/cm buffers, τm was considerably reduced and was as short as 1 μs. For larger cells (plant cells), the steady-state TMV will not be reached when using short (a few μs) pulses as described in most experiments. Permeabilization will require higher field than when using longer (ms duration) pulses. The induced TMV in dense cell suspensions is smaller due to shielding of cells by neighbors [26]. The effect of pulse delivery frequency on the plant tissue permeabilization showed that for the onion tissue, more permeabilization occurs when pulses are delivered at 1 Hz than at 5000 Hz [27].
